public interface TypeMap<V>
extends NavigableMap<Class<?>,​V>
A Map extension that returns a non-null value for a type if either the type itself or any of its super types is present in the map. This is useful if you want to define default values (or fall-back actions if the value type is a Function) for types that have not been explicitly added to the map.

Contrary to ordinary maps it is not permitted to add strictly duplicate keys. In other words, once a type is in the map, you cannot overwrite its value any longer. Also, it is not permitted to add a type if any of its super types has already been added to the map. Therefore you must add the lowest-level classes first and base classes and interfaces last. null keys and null values are not allowed. It is permitted to add Object.class but note that containsKey() will then always return true.

Contrary to the TreeMap class (the super class of ModifiableTypeMap and UnmodifiableTypeMap) you cannot specify your own Comparator for sorting the key set. You can, however, specify sort options that will be "appended" to an internally created Comparator.

Obviously this map implementation strongly violates the general Map contract.
